Afdød","1207–Female":"1207–Afdød","1140–Male":"1140–Afdød","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1198":"1198","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"1170–":"1170–Overleden","1170–Male":"1170–Overleden","1190–1257":"1190–1257","1198–Female":"1198–Overleden","1207–Female":"1207–Overleden","1140–Male":"1140–Overleden","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1198":"1198","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1170–":"1170–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1190–1257":"1190–1257","1198–Female":"1198–Deceased","1207–Female":"1207–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1198":"1198","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Reddish","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Reddish (Lancashire), recorded as <i>Rediche</i> in 1212 and <i>Reedyche</i> in 1325, Redditch in Tardebigge (Worcestershire), recorded as <i>la Rededich</i> in 1247, or perhaps from Reddish in Lymm (Cheshire), recorded as <i>Ruedis</i> in the 13th century, or Reddish in Taxal (Cheshire). The Lancashire placename probably derives from Old English <i>hrēod</i> ‘reed’ + <i>dīc</i> ‘ditch’. The Worcestershire placename derives from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>dīc</i>. Reddish in Lymm (Cheshire) derives from Old English <i>rūh</i> ‘rough’ + <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosure’. Reddish in Taxal (Cheshire) probably has the same etymology as the Lancashire placename."],"variants":[{"name":"Redish","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aaron David, Mendel.","English: variant of   Reddish  .","Jewish (from Bohemia; also <b>Redisch</b>): from the Yiddish name for the town Hradišt in Bohemia."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":54,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":89,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Reddish was born in 1170, in Manchester, Lancashire, England as the son of Roger de Reddish. He had at least 3 daughters."},"et":{"1170–":"1170–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1190–1257":"1190–1257","1198–Female":"1198–Surnud","1207–Female":"1207–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1198":"1198","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1170–":"1170–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1190–1257":"1190–1257","1198–Female":"1198–Kuollut","1207–Female":"1207–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1198":"1198","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1170–":"1170–Décédé","1170–Male":"1170–Décédé","1190–1257":"1190–1257","1198–Female":"1198–Décédée","1207–Female":"1207–Décédée","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1198":"1198","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Reddish est né en 1170, à Manchester, Lancashire, Angleterre, fils de Roger de Reddish. Il a eu au moins 3 filles."},"de":{"1170–":"1170–Verstorben","1170–Male":"1170–Verstorben","1190–1257":"1190–1257","1198–Female":"1198–Verstorben","1207–Female":"1207–Verstorben","1140–Male":"1140–Verstorben","1190":"1190","1259"